# CompSci
DriverPass: The Summary

The DriverPass project aimed to develop a scalable system for managing driving-related information, including user accounts, vehicle data, and driver records. The client required a solution that streamlined user management, assigned role-based permissions, and supported administrative tasks such as adding, editing, and removing user accounts (Cobb, 2015; Sommerville, 2016). The system needed to ensure data integrity, security, and efficient access control while maintaining a user-friendly experience. A key focus of the project was ensuring clear communication of roles and permissions within the system. To achieve this, I defined specific administrative functions aligned with business requirements. For instance: Admin could create, modify, or delete user accounts, assign roles, and manage access levels. The drivers could update their profiles, view vehicle records, and check license renewal dates. Support staff had limited access to assist users without modifying core data.
To communicate these roles effectively, I used (UML) diagrams, activity diagrams, and user account workflows. These tools helped visualize user interactions with the system and provided clarity for stakeholders (Pressman & Maxim, 2020). While the back-end architecture was well-structured, I identified UI and UX improvements as a potential enhancement. Although the system functioned efficiently, the interface could have been more intuitive. Research shows that systems with a well-designed user experience lead to higher adoption rates and reduced user errors (Norman, 2013; Nielsen, 1994).
To improve the UI, I’d incorporate Heuristic evaluation (Nielsen, 1994) to identify usability issues. User-centered design (UCD) principles, focusing on simplicity, accessibility, and intuitive navigation (Shneiderman et al., 2016). Early-stage user testing to gather feedback before final implementation, ensuring the interface met user expectations.
For example, instead of requiring users to navigate multiple menus to update vehicle records, a dashboard with quick-access widgets could simplify interactions and improve efficiency.
Understanding the end-users' needs was critical to the system’s success. To ensure the system met functional and business requirements, I applied a user-centered design approach, which included: user story mapping to define key functionalities such as user authentication, profile management, and role-based access control. Prototyping and iterative testing, ensuring adjustments could be made based on real user feedback. And finally, Agile development principles, allowing for continuous improvement and adaptability throughout the project (Cobb, 2015). For instance, during the development process, initial feedback suggested that role-based access was too complex, leading to confusion among users. By simplifying permission structures and integrating role templates, the system became more intuitive and manageable.
The DriverPass project successfully delivered a scalable, role-based system that streamlined user management and administrative processes. By prioritizing clear role definitions, structured workflows, and a secure back-end, the system met the client’s core requirements. However, improving UI and UX design through early-stage feedback and usability testing would have further enhanced system adoption and user satisfaction. Applying a user-centered approach and Agile methodologies ensured that the solution was both functional and adaptable to future business needs.

References
Cobb, C. G. (2015). The project manager’s guide to mastering Agile: Principles and practices for an adaptive approach. John Wiley & Sons, Inc.
Nielsen, J. (1994). Usability engineering. Morgan Kaufmann.
Norman, D. A. (2013). The design of everyday things. Basic Books.
Pressman, R. S., & Maxim, B. R. (2020). Software engineering: A practitioner’s approach (9th ed.). McGraw-Hill.
Shneiderman, B., Plaisant, C., Cohen, M., Jacobs, S., Elmqvist, N., & Diakopoulos, N. (2016). Designing the user interface: Strategies for effective human-computer interaction (6th ed.). Pearson.
Sommerville, I. (2016). Software engineering (10th ed.). Pearson.

